## Project Context

**arch-btw** is a single-player system-design interview practice tool. Users drag infrastructure components onto a tldraw canvas, connect them, then enter a turn-based PR-review loop with an LLM critic. It ends with a structured scorecard debrief.

**Stack:** Next.js App Router (React 19) · TypeScript strict · Tailwind + shadcn/ui · tldraw · Drizzle ORM + Neon Postgres · Better Auth + GitHub OAuth · Vercel AI SDK (streamText + generateObject) · hosted on Vercel · **Vitest** for unit/integration tests.

**Key decisions:**
- Canvas: tldraw with 12 custom ShapeUtils (Service/API, Worker, Queue/Stream, SQL DB, NoSQL, Cache, Object storage, Gateway/LB, Third-party API, LLM provider, Webhook source, Cron + Custom)
- LLM: swappable via env key (GEMINI_API_KEY / ANTHROPIC_API_KEY / OPENAI_API_KEY), all server-side
- Serialization: tldraw store → `{ nodes, edges, notes }` JSON via a tested adapter; store both tldraw snapshot AND derived graph JSON
- Auth: Better Auth (NOT Auth.js) + GitHub OAuth
- DB: Drizzle + Neon. Scorecard uses Zod, shared between AI SDK / DB JSON column / React render.
- Test runner: Vitest. New modules need tests. If no `vitest.config.ts` exists yet, create one.

**Read `docs/CONTEXT.md` for full decision log before implementing.**

**Neon MCP is available.** For any database work (running migrations, inspecting schema, verifying connectivity, running ad-hoc SQL) use the Neon MCP tools directly — no need to shell out to `psql` or `neonctl`. The project ID is in the Neon console; the connection strings are in `.env`.

